  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a caveat appears on a property title in Queensland, it effectively freezes dealings with that land. A buyer's solicitor will spot it immediately during the title search, and the conveyancing process cannot proceed until it is resolved. For sellers who have not anticipated this, a caveat can cause significant delays or, in the worst cases, cause a buyer to walk away from the transaction entirely. Understanding what a caveat is, why one might appear on your title, and what removing it actually involves is essential knowledge before you list.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a caveat is and what it does</h2>
      <p>A caveat is a formal notice registered on a property title under the Land Title Act 1994 (Qld). It signals that a third party (the caveator) claims an interest in the land. That interest could be an equitable interest, a contractual right, a charge over the property, or any number of other recognised legal claims. Once a caveat is lodged and registered with Titles Queensland, the Registrar cannot register any further dealing with that land without either the caveator's consent or a court order removing the caveat.</p>

      <p>This is not a minor administrative inconvenience. It means your transfer at settlement cannot be registered. A buyer who settles on a property with a caveat still on title does not receive unencumbered ownership, and their lender will not advance funds against a title in that condition. The practical effect is that a caveat must be dealt with before settlement can occur.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who can lodge a caveat and why</h2>
      <p>Only a person or entity with a caveatable interest can validly lodge a caveat in Queensland. Lodging a caveat without a proper legal basis is a serious matter and can expose the caveator to a compensation claim from the property owner. That said, the Registrar does not investigate the merits of the claim when a caveat is lodged, so a caveat can sit on a title even if the underlying claim is weak or disputed.</p>

      <p>The most common reasons a caveat appears on a seller's title include:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Unpaid debts and charges.</strong> A creditor who is owed money and has obtained a judgment, or who holds a charge over the property as security for a debt, can lodge a caveat to protect their position.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Option agreements and contracts.</strong> If you have previously signed an option agreement giving someone the right to purchase the property, that person can caveat their interest. The same applies to a prior contract for sale that has not been formally terminated.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Family law and relationship property claims.</strong> A former partner may lodge a caveat claiming an equitable interest in the property arising from a de facto relationship or marriage, particularly if they contributed financially to its purchase or improvement.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Disputed ownership and constructive trusts.</strong> Someone who argues they contributed to the purchase price or improvements under circumstances that give rise to a constructive trust may caveat their claimed equitable interest.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Unpaid purchase money.</strong> In some vendor finance arrangements, the original seller may retain a caveat over the land until the purchase price is fully paid.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a caveat blocks a property sale</h2>
      <p>When your solicitor runs a title search in preparation for listing, or when a buyer's solicitor searches the title after contract execution, the caveat will appear in the title records. Your solicitor has an obligation to disclose it, and the buyer's solicitor will require confirmation of how and when it will be removed before their client proceeds to settlement.</p>

      <p>If the caveat is not dealt with, your conveyancer cannot register the transfer at settlement. In Queensland, settlement is the point at which the transfer is lodged with Titles Queensland and the purchase price is exchanged. A transfer cannot be registered over a caveated title without the caveator's withdrawal, a court order removing the caveat, or a lapsing process under the Land Title Act. Settlement will not proceed until one of these outcomes is in place.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to remove a caveat in Queensland</h2>
      <p>There are three main paths to removing a caveat in Queensland, and the right approach depends on whether the caveator has a legitimate claim and whether they are willing to engage.</p>

      <p><strong>Negotiated withdrawal.</strong> If the caveator's underlying claim is legitimate and quantifiable (for example, a debt that is genuinely owed), the most straightforward path is to resolve the underlying dispute. Once the debt is paid or the claim settled, the caveator lodges a Withdrawal of Caveat with Titles Queensland. This can happen relatively quickly if all parties cooperate, and is by far the most efficient outcome.</p>

      <p><strong>Lapsing notice.</strong> If the caveator refuses to withdraw or cannot be engaged, you can serve a lapsing notice through Titles Queensland. Once served, the caveator has 14 days to obtain a court order extending the caveat. If they do not obtain that order within 14 days, the caveat lapses automatically. The lapsing notice process requires care, as improperly served notices can invalidate the process. Your solicitor should manage this.</p>

      <p><strong>Court application.</strong> If the caveator obtains an extension or if you need to challenge the caveat's validity directly, an application to the Supreme Court of Queensland may be required. This is the most time-consuming and costly path, though injunctions can sometimes be obtained relatively quickly where the circumstances are urgent. Courts in Queensland are generally willing to remove caveats that are lodged without a proper caveatable interest.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long removal takes and what it means for your sale timeline</h2>
      <p>The timeline depends heavily on the path taken. A negotiated withdrawal where the caveator cooperates can be completed in days. A lapsing notice takes a minimum of around 14 days after service, plus the time required for preparation and lodgement. A contested court application can take weeks to months depending on the complexity of the underlying claim and court availability.</p>

      <p>For sellers in the middle of a campaign, a caveat that cannot be resolved quickly creates real pressure. Buyers typically have a right to terminate a contract if special conditions relating to title are not satisfied, and an unresolved caveat will trigger that right in most standard Queensland contracts. Extending a settlement date is possible if the buyer is willing, but it is not guaranteed, and sophisticated buyers may use the delay to renegotiate price or terms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if you discover a caveat before listing</h2>
      <p>The most important step is to engage a property solicitor or conveyancer before you list, not after you have accepted an offer. A title search prior to listing costs very little and will reveal any caveats, encumbrances, easements, or other interests on the title. If a caveat appears, your solicitor can advise on whether the underlying claim appears legitimate, how to approach the caveator, and what the likely resolution timeline looks like.</p>

      <p>Where the caveat relates to a clear and undisputed debt, the path forward is usually straightforward: settle the debt, obtain the withdrawal, and list once the title is clean. Where the caveat relates to a disputed family law claim or a contested interest, the matter may need to be resolved through negotiation or proceedings before you can sell, and your solicitor should advise you on the realistic timeline and costs involved before you commit to a campaign.</p>

      <p>Discovering a caveat mid-campaign, after a buyer has made an offer, is the worst position to be in. The pressure of an existing contract, with a buyer who may be financing their purchase and has their own settlement deadline, significantly reduces your leverage in resolving the caveat on favourable terms. Dealing with it before you list gives you control over the timeline and avoids the risk of a buyer walking away.</p>

